Create the Boxplot We will create a boxplot that displays engine size (displ) per car class (class) with the following customizations:

Individual Data Points: Color the points based on the car manufacturer. Change Theme: Use the classic theme. Set Axis Limits: Set the y-axis limits from 0 to 10. Remove Outliers: Exclude outliers from the boxplot. # Create the boxplot with customizations

ggplot(cars, aes(x = class, y = displ, color = manufacturer)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # Hide outliers
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.6, width = 0.2) +  # Add data points with jitter
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 10)) +  # Set y-axis limits from 0 to 10
  theme_classic() +  # Change the theme to "classic"
  labs(
    title = "Engine Size by Car Class",
    x = "Car Class",
    y = "Engine Size (L)"
  )

#Explanation ggplot(mpg, aes(x = class, y = displ, color = manufacturer)): Specifies the dataset (mpg) and maps the class to the x-axis, displ (engine size) to the y-axis, and manufacturer to the color aesthetic for the points. geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA): Creates a boxplot and hides outliers by setting outlier.shape = NA. geom_jitter(alpha = 0.6, width = 0.2): Adds individual data points to the plot with slight horizontal jitter to avoid overlapping points. The alpha parameter adjusts the transparency, and the width controls the horizontal spread of the points. scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 10)): Customizes the y-axis limits to range from 0 to 10. theme_classic(): Applies the classic theme for a clean look. labs(): Adds informative titles and axis labels for better understanding.

#further illustrations/plots using piping, ggplot2 and functions Below is an script that includes multiple ggplot2 visualizations using the mpg dataset. It also incorporates pipes (%>% from dplyr) and simple functions to manipulate and visualize data effectively.

This script includes:

A scatter plot of engine size vs.highway MPG. A boxplot showing highway MPG per car class. A bar chart of the number of cars per manufacturer. A density plot of highway MPG. It also provides explanations through comments in the code. You can copy and paste it directly into an RMarkdown file and knit it to an HTML or PDF report.

Scatter plot of engine displacement vs highway MPG

car <- mpg  # Assign dataset to variable "car"
car %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.7, size = 3) +  # Scatter points with transparency
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +  # Add trend line
  labs(
    title = "Engine Size vs Highway MPG",
    x = "Engine Displacement (L)",
    y = "Highway MPG",
    color = "Car Class"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()  # Use a clean theme
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Boxplot of highway MPG per car class
car %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = hwy, fill = class)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +  # Remove outliers
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, alpha = 0.5) +  # Add jittered points
  labs(
    title = "Highway MPG by Car Class",
    x = "Car Class",
    y = "Highway MPG"
  ) +
  theme_classic()  # Use a classic theme

# Count number of cars per manufacturer
car %>%
  count(manufacturer) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(manufacturer, n), y = n, fill = manufacturer)) +
  geom_col() +  # Bar chart
  coord_flip() +  # Flip for better readability
  labs(
    title = "Number of Cars per Manufacturer",
    x = "Manufacturer",
    y = "Count of Cars"
  ) +
  theme_light()  # Use a light theme

# Density plot of highway MPG
car %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = hwy, fill = class)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +  # Add transparency
  labs(
    title = "Density Plot of Highway MPG",
    x = "Highway MPG",
    y = "Density"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()  # Use a minimal theme

#Functions are a great way to make your RMarkdown code cleaner, reusable, and modular. Below is an RMarkdown script that defines custom functions to create ggplots using the mpg dataset. This makes the code more organized and reusable.

#1. Function for a Scatter Plot This function creates a scatter plot of displ vs.hwy and allows customization of color.

plot_scatter <- function(data, color_var = "class") {
  data %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = .data[[color_var]])) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.7, size = 3) +  # Transparent points
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +  # Trend line
    labs(
      title = "Engine Size vs Highway MPG",
      x = "Engine Displacement (L)",
      y = "Highway MPG",
      color = "Car Attribute"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()  # Clean theme
}

#Now, lets use this function:

car <- mpg  # Assign dataset to "car"
plot_scatter(car, color_var = "manufacturer")  # Call function with custom color
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
